In LATEX, we can use the `tocloft` package to automatically generate a table of contents. Here's an example:

```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tocloft}

% Define the sections in the document
\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Background}
This is the background section.

\section{Methods}
This is the methods section.

\section{Results}
This is the results section.

\section{Discussion}
This is the discussion section.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion section.

\begin{document}

% Generate the table of contents
\tableofcontents

% Insert the sections in the document
\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Background}
This is the background section.

\section{Methods}
This is the methods section.

\section{Results}
This is the results section.

\section{Discussion}
This is the discussion section.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion section.

\end{document}
```

In this example, we first load the `tocloft` package using `\usepackage{tocloft}`. Then, we define our sections in the document using the `\section` command.

To generate the table of contents, we use the `\tableofcontents` command. This command automatically generates a table of contents based on the `\section` commands in the document.

Finally, we insert the sections in the document using the appropriate `\section` commands.

That's it! This is a simple example of how to generate a table of contents automatically in a LATEX document using the `tocloft` package.

